#: Game.Levels.SubsetWorld.L13_Antisymm
msgid "¬ß0 gives you a one-step path from two ‚äÜ proofs to\n"
"set equality. Compare the two routes:\n"
"\n"
"| Route | When to use |\n"
"|---|---|\n"
"| ¬ß1 | When you need to prove both directions from scratch |\n"
"| ¬ß2 | When you already have both ‚äÜ proofs in hand |\n"
"\n"
"In practice, many set equality proofs start with ¬ß3 because you\n"
"rarely have the subset proofs pre-packaged. But ¬ß4 is\n"
"valuable when subset facts are available from other lemmas or\n"
"hypotheses.\n"
"\n"
"In ordinary math, this is the well-known principle: \"two sets are\n"
"equal iff each is a subset of the other.\" Every proof of set equality\n"
"by \"double inclusion\" (showing ‚äÜ in both directions) is implicitly\n"
"using antisymmetry.\n"
"\n"
"A **partial order** is a relation that satisfies three properties:\n"
"1. **Reflexive**: ¬ß5 for all ¬ß6\n"
"2. **Transitive**: ¬ß7 and ¬ß8 imply ¬ß9\n"
"3. **Antisymmetric**: ¬ß10 and ¬ß11 imply ¬ß12\n"
"\n"
"You have now proved all three for ¬ß13 on ¬ß14:\n"
"- **Reflexive**: ¬ß15 (Level 3)\n"
"- **Transitive**: ¬ß16 (Level 8)\n"
"- **Antisymmetric**: ¬ß17 (this level)\n"
"\n"
"Together, these make ¬ß18 a **partial order** on sets. The partial\n"
"order concept is central to mathematics ‚Äî you will study it in depth\n"
"in the Orders \\\\& Lattices course.\n"
"\n"
"These two routes ‚Äî ¬ß19 and ¬ß20 ‚Äî are logically *equivalent*.\n"
"You can derive ¬ß21 from ¬ß22 and ¬ß23 from ¬ß24. You\n"
"will prove this equivalence yourself in Levels 15 and 16."
msgstr ""

