#: Game.Levels.SubsetWorld
msgid "# Subset World\n"
"\n"
"In Set World, you learned that sets are predicates and membership is\n"
"predicate evaluation. Now you will learn the two fundamental\n"
"relationships between sets: **subset** (¬ß0) and **equality** (¬ß1).\n"
"\n"
"A **subset** proof ¬ß2 means: for every element, if it is in ¬ß3\n"
"then it is in ¬ß4. The proof shape is always ¬ß5 ‚Äî fix an\n"
"element, assume it is in the smaller set, then show it is in the\n"
"larger set.\n"
"\n"
"A **set equality** proof ¬ß6 means: the two sets have exactly the\n"
"same elements. There are two routes:\n"
"- **Extensionality** (¬ß7): prove ¬ß8 directly\n"
"- **Double containment** (¬ß9): prove ¬ß10 and\n"
"  ¬ß11 separately\n"
"\n"
"By the end of this world, you will:\n"
"- Prove subset relations with the ¬ß12 pattern\n"
"- Handle the boundary cases ¬ß13 and ¬ß14\n"
"- Use subset hypotheses as functions\n"
"- Disprove false subset claims by contradiction\n"
"- Chain subset proofs transitively\n"
"- Prove set equality via ¬ß15 (extensionality)\n"
"- Prove set equality via ¬ß16 (double containment)\n"
"- Prove set non-equality by finding a contradictory witness\n"
"- Prove proper subset (¬ß17) by combining ¬ß18 and ¬ß19\n"
"- Use ¬ß20 to unwrap set notation on hypotheses\n"
"\n"
"You will also gain a new tactic (¬ß21) and a new proof strategy\n"
"(double containment) that you will use throughout the rest of this\n"
"course.\n"
"\n"
"**New tools in this world**:\n"
"- ¬ß22 ‚Äî unwrap a hypothesis to a definitionally equal form\n"
"- ¬ß23 ‚Äî reduce set equality to element-wise membership\n"
"- ¬ß24 ‚Äî derive equality from mutual subsets"
msgstr ""

